http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: The State Curriculum defines what students should know and be able to do at each grade level in Physical Education.

Skillfulness - Students will demonstrate the ability to enhance their performance of a variety of physical skills by developing fundamental movement skills, creating original skill combinations, combining skills effectively in skill themes, and applying skills.
Fundamental Movement
Show fundamental movement skills.
Demonstrate locomotor skills including walking, jogging, running, galloping, hopping, and jumping.
Use general spatial awareness and self-space awareness in physical activity.
Demonstrate non-locomotor skills of bending and stretching.
Demonstrate non-locomotor skills of bending, pulling, stretching, twisting, turning, pushing, and swinging.
Demonstrate a variety of locomotor skills using various speeds.
Demonstrate locomotor skills including walking, jogging, running, galloping, jumping, sliding, hopping, skipping, and leaping.
Exhibit general spatial awareness and self-space awareness, using a variety of directions, levels, and pathways.
Demonstrate the combination of non-locomotor and locomotor skills in coordinated movement patterns.
Demonstrate proper techniques of take-offs and landings.
Identify and perform movement skills of chasing and fleeing.
Show proficiency in all locomotor skills.
Exhibit general spatial awareness and self-space awareness using various directions, levels, and pathways while performing different locomotor skills.
Demonstrate and combine non-locomotor and locomotor skills in physical activity settings.
Demonstrate the fundamental movement skills such as: throwing, catching, kicking, and striking.
Demonstrate evasion skills of chasing, fleeing, and dodging in a variety of physical activities.
Demonstrate and apply fundamental movement skills in an authentic situation.
Show non-locomotor and locomotor skills in complex movement patterns including the elements of speed, pathways, directionality, levels, and space.
Identify and use fundamental movement skills such as: throwing, catching, kicking, and striking in a game or an activity.
Identify and show activities that enhance the skill-related fitness components: power, speed, reaction time, agility, balance, and coordination.

Use non-locomotor and locomotor skills while varying movement conditions such as: speed, force, pathways, directions, levels, and space in authentic situations such as: fitness, adventure and cooperative games, rhythms and dance, tumbling and gymnastics, recreational games, individual and team sports.

Classify and show the fundamental movement skills needed in a variety of physical activities such as: fitness, adventure and cooperative games, rhythms and dance, tumbling and gymnastics, recreational games, individual and team sports.
Evaluate fundamental movement skills in a variety of physical education activities.

Compare fundamental movement skills that will enhance skill themes in physical activities such as: fitness, adventure and cooperative games, rhythms and dance, tumbling and gymnastics, recreational games, individual and team sports.

Assess personal fundamental movement skills, skill combinations, and skill themes in a variety of small group physical activity settings such as: fitness, adventure and cooperative games, rhythms and dance, tumbling and gymnastics, recreational games, individual and team sports.

Assess a peer for fundamental movement skills, skill combinations, and skill themes in a variety of small and large group physical activity settings such as: fitness, adventure and cooperative games, rhythms and dance, tumbling and gymnastics, recreational games, individual and team sports.
Choose and analyze fundamental movement skills in a variety of physical education activities.
Demonstrate and differentiate fundamental movement skills, skill combinations, and skill themes while participating in physical activity.
Categorize and perform a selection of activities that improve or maintain skill-related components of fitness.
Creative Movement
Show Creative Movement
Identify different body parts and demonstrate a variety of ways they can move.
Demonstrate spatial concepts of big, small, tall, and short in a variety of movement patterns.
Use the body to show a variety of different shapes such as: curved, narrow, and wide.
Perform a variety of movements using the body to interpret a poem, story, or song.
Move the body symmetrically and asymmetrically while maintaining balance in a stationary position.
Display a smooth transition between locomotor and non-locomotor skills in time to music.
Perform a variety of movements using the body and implements to interpret a given situation, such as: a poem, story, or song.
Move the body symmetrically and asymmetrically while traveling in general space.
Demonstrate creative movement skills
Use an individual movement sequence to exhibit emotions, expressions and feelings using implements such as: wands, hoops, balls, rhythm sticks, jump bands, and tinikling sticks.
Perform creative movements in an individual/partner sequence with or without the use of implements.
Perform a creative individual/partner/group movement sequence using a movement theme, music, or other rhythmic accompaniment.
Evaluate creative skill combinations in a variety of physical activities.
Compare and contrast two creative movement patterns for common themes such as: self expression, rhythmical interpretation, form, or style.
Assess an individual/partner performance sequence that exhibits quality movement based on common themes such as: self expression, rhythmical interpretation, form, or style.
Justify a personal opinion for an individual or partner performance sequence that exhibits quality movement based on common themes such as: self expression, rhythmical interpretation, form, or style.
Develop and critique creative skill combinations in a variety of physical activities.
Design, demonstrate, and evaluate a group creative performance sequence that exhibits quality movement based on common themes such as: self expression, rhythmical interpretation, form, or style.
Skill Themes
Show skill themes
Demonstrate rolling a ball at an object.
Demonstrate throwing a ball.
Demonstrate striking a lightweight object with different body parts.
Demonstrate catching a self-tossed lightweight object such as: a scarf or a balloon.
Use and demonstrate opposition with hand/foot when using underhand tosses and overhand throws.
Demonstrate catching an overhand thrown object while stationary.
Use and demonstrate opposition and shoulder rotation when throwing overhand.
Demonstrate striking a lightweight object with different body parts.
Demonstrate catching a self-bounced ball.
Demonstrate throwing objects using an underhand and overhand throwing pattern.
Demonstrate balance on a variety of body parts.
Demonstrate transferring weight between different body parts.
Demonstrate striking objects with various body parts and short handled implements.
Exhibit maintaining balance on a base of support while changing body shapes.
Display transferring weight from feet to hand such as: a frog jump or cartwheel.
Demonstrate a variety of tumbling experiences.
Display transfer of weight when striking objects using various implements.
Display a tumbling sequence using balance, weight transfer, and rolling.
Use a tumbling sequence that includes balance, weight transfer, and various body shapes.
Demonstrate skill themes
Use individual skill themes while moving by including throwing, catching, and striking in group games or activities.
Show a mature pattern when catching and throwing.
Apply skill themes
Demonstrate and combine skill themes in physical activity including throwing, catching, and striking with control in an authentic setting.
Demonstrate a self-designed tumbling sequence that includes three skills.
Demonstrate skill themes including basic offensive and defensive strategies such as: creating space on offense and preventing scoring on defense in games and activities.
Demonstrate a self-designed tumbling sequence that includes a beginning and ending shape, and skills for rolling, transfer of weight, and balance.
Analyze strategies to solve tactical game problems
Organize physical activities into the four basic categories of tactical games (net/wall, invasion, striking/fielding, and target).
Categorize movement concepts and strategies used in each game category such as: on-the-ball skills and off-the-ball movements.
Organize and choose different concepts/ strategies for each tactical game category (net/wall, invasion, striking/fielding, and target).
Investigate the importance of utilizing offensive and defensive strategies in game category in relationship to scoring and preventing scoring.
Investigate and use different concepts/strategies for each tactical game category (net/wall, invasion, striking/fielding, and target) such as: scoring and preventing scoring.
Compare and choose movement strategies that add to student success during participation in net/wall, invasion, striking/fielding, and target activities.
Evaluate the performance and strategies used to solve tactical game problems.

Justify and use different concepts and strategies for each category of strategic games (net/wall, invasion, striking/fielding, and target activities) such as: offensive and defensive strategies or on and off the ball movements.
Biomechanical Principles - Students will demonstrate an ability to use the principles of biomechanics to generate and control force to improve their movement effectiveness and safety.
Effects on Objects
Identify ways that people and objects move.
Show how how a body moves fast and slow.
Show how to move a body forward, backward, and sideways in open space.
Show how an object's motion can be changed such as: speeding up from a standstill, slowing down to a stop, going faster, and going slower.
Display how lowering the body's center of gravity (bending the knees) and widening the base of support (stance) will help to stop the body safely and under control.
Display how changing the force applied to an object changes the distance it will travel. (More force equals greater distance.)
Show how to reduce the impact of a force such as: bending the knees when landing after a jump.
Display how changing the angle of an object when thrown, kicked, or released changes the distance and direction it will travel.
Show how to reduce the speed of a thrown object such as: bending the elbows when catching a ball.
Explain how force causes change in the way objects move.
Discuss and demonstrate how increasing or decreasing the size, number, or speed of body parts tends to increase or decrease the force generated.
Discuss and demonstrate how faster movement produces greater force.
Describe how the changes in motion of objects are determined by the mass of an object and the amount of the force applied to it.
Demonstrate and describe for every action there is an equal and opposite reaction such as: dribbling a ball with a light force produces a small rebound and a heavy force produces a large rebound.

Demonstrate and discuss how the changes in motion of objects are determined by the mass of an object and the amount of the force applied to it. Examples such as a yarn ball, whiffle ball, or softball (same size, different mass) will travel different distances when thrown with the same force.
Demonstrate and discuss how raising the body's center of gravity and narrowing the base of support allows for quicker starts such as: runners leaning forward to start a race.
Apply the concept of force in relationship to how objects move.
Calculate and demonstrate how applying force effects the movement of a projectile.
Explain and show how absorption of force increases control such as: sport examples of bunting a softball, collecting a soccer ball, catching a football.
Explain and show how efficient movements decrease injuries in a variety of activities such as: striking a soccer ball with the instep instead of the toes.
Demonstrate how to apply and control force of a projectile in order to move it toward a stationary target.
Demonstrate and discuss how longer and/or heavier implements such as: bats and clubs tend to produce more force than shorter or lighter ones.

Demonstrate and discuss how efficient movements decrease injuries in a variety of activities to improve fitness such as: bending knees to only 90 degrees when completing a squat lift to develop muscular strength.
Demonstrate how to change and control the amount of force applied to a projectile in order to move it toward a moving target.
Calculate and show how accuracy of projectiles is dependent on factors such as: speed of projectile, distance from target, weight of object, size of the implement, and number of body parts used.
Choose and integrate efficient movements in order to decrease injuries in a variety of activities
Analyze how muscle characteristics influence force production.
Categorize and demonstrate how the number of muscles engaged in a movement affects force production.
Choose and demonstrate how the size of muscle engaged affects the force produced.
Contrast and demonstrate how the distance through which a muscle contracts affects the force produced.
Investigate and demonstrate how forcefully stretching a muscle immediately before a concentric contraction increases the force of that contraction such as in plyometrics.
Analyze how force is effectively applied to projectiles.
Distinguish and demonstrate how projection speed and projection angle are related to accuracy such as: striking a tennis ball using a smash or a lob to have it land in the back corner of the court.
Calculate and demonstrate the concept of projection angles such as changing the projection angle to discover the influence on distance achieved.
Investigate and demonstrate the effect of spin such as in tennis when topspin rebounds on a higher trajectory and backspin rebounds on a lower trajectory.
Investigate and demonstrate how balls can generate lift by spinning such as in soccer.
Balance
Identify balance through movement.
Show the ability to balance on one or more body parts.
Demonstrate static and dynamic balance.
Show the ability to balance on one or more body parts.
Show dynamic and static balances through movement.
Display a base of support when maintaining balance.
Show static balance using symmetrical and asymmetrical shapes.
Explain and display the importance of a base of support and center of gravity when maintaining balance.
Explain and demonstrate static and dynamic balance in various movement patterns.
Show the difference between static and dynamic balance while maintaining body control.
Discuss factors that influence static balance positions while maintaining balance such as: weight, center of gravity, foot size, and previous experience.

Discuss factors that influence dynamic balance in a variety of physical activities such as: weight, center of gravity, foot size, and previous experience that influence one's balance while walking on a balance beam.
Show a movement pattern that includes static and dynamic balance such as: a throw or a kick in a variety of physical activities and describe how balance affects performance.
Analyze the concept of balance in complex movement patterns.
Explore how the center of gravity effects balance and performance during a variety of movement activities.
Compare how changing levels while moving effects your center of gravity and performance.
Investigate how changes in the center of gravity affect balance and performance in a variety of physical activities.
Investigate changes in the center of gravity and balance of a dynamic skill such as a basketball lay-up.

Motor Learning Principles - Students will demonstrate the ability to use motor skill principles to learn and develop proficiency through frequent practice opportunities in which skills are repeatedly performed correctly in a variety of situations.
Appropriate Practices
Recognize that skills will develop over time with appropriate practice and use of the correct cues.
Show basic motor skills, using imitation, as a means for motor skill improvement.
Demonstrate fundamental movement skills and skill themes using teacher cues for skill improvement.
Identify and demonstrate the critical cues for fundamental movement skills.
Name and demonstrate progression cues that will enhance various fundamental movement skills.
Apply and show that skills will develop over time with appropriate practice
Use critical progression cues for object control skills in a variety of physical activities for skill improvement.
Demonstrate skill progressions to enhance personal skill development in a variety of settings.
Employ a variety of acquired skills in order to demonstrate skill proficiency.
Justify that skills will develop over time with appropriate practice.
Assess and rate improvement of skills learned in a closed or isolated environment (closed skills).
Rate and predict improvement for various personal skills learned in an open or changing environment.
Design a practice plan in order to acquire a skill and apply the skill in a game.
Compare the similarities and differences between closed and open skills.
Discuss and demonstrate how proficient performance of closed skills results in sustained quality performance in game situations.
Predict factors to consider when performing open skills in a game situation such as the environment and skill level.
Develop a practice plan to progressively introduce closed skills into open skill environments.
Corrective Feedback
Identify the importance of corrective feedback on performance.
Use verbal and visual cues to improve skill performance.
Recall and show verbal and visual cues to improve personal performance in a variety of skills.
List and show examples of appropriate feedback using verbal and visual cues to improve performance in a specific skill.
Use corrective feedback for improvement in skill performance.
Interpret and apply feedback using verbal and visual cues to show improved performance in a variety of skills.
Interpret errors in personal skill performance based on corrective feedback.
Provide feedback to illustrate errors in a peer's skill performance.
Apply feedback to solve and correct errors in personal skill performance.
Provide feedback to solve and correct errors in a peer's performance.
Investigate the importance of self-evaluation and feedback in the improvement of motor skills.
Organize a checklist to correct errors in skills for improvement in personal performance.
Analyze and improve a specific motor skill based on feedback and discussion.
Organize a practice plan, based on a checklist, to correct errors in skills to improve performance for self or a peer.
Analyze and improve a combination of motor skills based on peer feedback.
Analyze and appraise a practice plan for skill improvement based on a checklist for self or peers.
Analyze and improve a complex motor task based on a plan of improvement.
Justify the importance of self-evaluation and feedback in the improvement of motor skills.
Create, perform, and evaluate a practice plan for skill improvement based on a checklist developed from an evaluation by self or peers.

Exercise Physiology - Students will demonstrate the ability to use scientific principles to design and participate in a regular, moderate to vigorous physical activity program that contributes to personal health and enhances cognitive and physical performance in a variety of academic, recreational, and life tasks.
Effects of Physical Activity on the Body
Identify the effects of physical activity on the body systems.
Demonstrate how exercise affects the body. For example, the body sweats, the heart beats faster, and the lungs work harder.
List and demonstrate the functions of specific muscles of the muscular system.
Locate various places on the body to determine the heart's response to aerobic activity.
Recognize the relationship between the muscular and skeletal systems during physical activity and show how the muscles move the bones.
Explain and demonstrate the effect of moderate to vigorous physical activity on the body systems.
Identify selected bones such as leg, arm, spine, and ribs and show how these bones help move select body parts during exercise.
Discuss why the body needs more oxygen when exercising and show how exercise results in an increased breathing rate.
Discuss the role of flexibility on the muscular system during physical activity and show various stretching exercises.
Explain the effect of moderate to vigorous physical activity on the body systems.
Discuss the function of the components of the cardiorespiratory system such as: the heart, lungs, blood vessels and describe how each functions during exercise.
Describe the role of the muscles and skeleton in the protection of the internal organs such as: the rib cage protecting the heart and lungs.
Select and show activities that develop the cardiorespiratory and muscular systems.
Discuss the function of the components of the skeletal and muscular systems such as: bones, cartilage, ligaments, and tendons.
Demonstrate how the cardio respiratory and muscular systems respond to exercise during the warm-up, aerobic, and cool-down phases of physical activity.
Classify and demonstrate activities that develop the cardiorespiratory and muscular systems.
Analyze the effect of moderate to vigorous physical activity on the body systems.
Discuss the three components of the central nervous system, brain, spinal cord, and neurons.
Discuss the functions of the central nervous system needed for physical activity such as: sending and receiving messages from other body systems and controlling all thoughts and movements.
Discuss the function of neurons such as: carrying information from the rest of the body to the spinal cord and bringing messages from the spinal cord to the appropriate body parts.
Investigate the function of the spinal cord such as: taking information from the neurons to the brain and taking messages from the brain back to the neurons.

Investigate the function of the brain when the body is participating in physical activity such as: cerebellum controls balance and coordination, the brain stem controls digestion, and heart beat, and the cerebral cortex controls the senses.
Evaluate the effects of moderate to vigorous physical activity on the body systems.
Defend a fitness plan using knowledge of the body systems and principles of overload, progression, specificity, regularity, and individuality.
FITT Guidelines
Identify components of the FITT guidelines.
Demonstrate specific activities that show the FITT guidelines for the component: Type.
Explain and apply the components of the FITT guidelines.
Discuss and perform specific activities that show the FITT guidelines for the components: Type and Intensity.
Discuss and perform specific activities that include the FITT guidelines for the components: Type, Intensity, and Time.
Describe the relationship between the FITT guidelines for the components: Frequency, Intensity, Type and Time.
Discuss and use the components of the FITT guidelines to develop a short-term fitness goal.
Analyze and evaluate components of the FITT guidelines to adjust levels of physical activity.
Develop and explore personal fitness goals.
Organize a fitness plan using the FITT guidelines.
Investigate the principles of overload, progression, specificity, regularity, and individuality.
Identify personal fitness goals based on a fitness assessment.
Choose and implement a fitness plan using the FITT guidelines.
Compare the principles of overload, progression, specificity, regularity, and individuality to improve health related fitness.
Revise personal fitness goals based on a fitness assessment.
Choose, implement, and assess, a personal fitness plan based on the FITT guidelines.
Defend the relationship between improved health related fitness and the principles of overload, progression, specificity, regularity, and individuality.
Evaluate the components of the FITT guidelines to adjust levels of physical activity.
Justify personal fitness goals based on fitness assessments.
Defend the use of components of the FITT guidelines in a personal fitness plan for consistency with fitness levels and goals.
Components of Fitness
Identify the components of fitness.
List and demonstrate activities that promote fitness for a healthy lifestyle.
List and demonstrate activities that increase heart rate and develop cardiorespiratory endurance.
List and demonstrate activities that improve cardiorespiratory endurance/aerobic capacity, muscular strength, muscular endurance, and flexibility.
Analyze the components necessary to improve fitness
Choose and perform activities that improve cardio respiratory endurance/aerobic capacity, muscular strength, muscular endurance, and flexibility.
Classify and show activities for each health-related fitness component: cardio respiratory endurance/aerobic capacity, muscular strength, muscular endurance, flexibility, and body composition.

Investigate activities that will improve the health-related fitness components: cardio respiratory endurance/aerobic capacity, muscular strength, muscular endurance, flexibility, and body composition.
Classify and show activities according to the skill-related components of fitness: agility, balance, coordination, power, speed, and reaction time.
Use the skill-related fitness components: agility, balance, coordination, power, speed, and reaction time through participation in selected activities.
Evaluate the components necessary to design a fitness plan.

Predict activities that maintain or improve the specific health-related fitness components: cardio respiratory endurance/aerobic capacity, muscular strength, muscular endurance, flexibility, and body composition.
Justify activities chosen to improve or maintain specific health-related fitness components.
Defend the selection of activities chosen to improve or maintain health-related fitness.
Identify, compare, and implement the components of a fitness plan such as: goals, baseline scores, and physical activity log.

Assess for improvement the skill-related fitness components: agility, balance, coordination, power, speed, and reaction time using standard performance measurements such as: 40 yard dash, shuttle run, vertical jump, and balance beam travel.
Choose, implement, and assess a fitness plan using the health-related fitness components.
Choose activities that will provide opportunities to improve or maintain specific personal skill-related fitness components as part of personal goal setting.
Choose, implement, assess, and defend a personal fitness plan using the health-related fitness components.
Justify the selection of the activities performed to improve or maintain skill-related fitness.
Assess a peer's personal goals to improve or maintain the skill- related components of fitness through selected activities.
Evaluate the various components necessary to design a personal fitness plan.
Assess the physiological benefits achieved through the implementation of a personal fitness plan.
Defend a personal fitness plan based on an assessment of the health-related fitness components and personal fitness goals.
Justify activities chosen to improve or maintain specific skill-related fitness components agility, balance, coordination, reaction time, speed, and power as part of a personal fitness plan.
Benefits of Physical Activity
Recognize the benefits of physical activity.
Specify the physical benefits of exercise.
State the physical benefits from activities that will improve fitness.
State the physical benefits developed for each of the health related fitness components: cardio respiratory endurance/aerobic capacity, muscular strength, muscular endurance, and flexibility.
Explain the benefits of physical activity.

Discuss the physical benefits developed for each of the health related fitness components: cardio respiratory endurance/aerobic capacity, muscular strength, muscular endurance, flexibility, and body composition.
Discuss the physical benefits of participation in physical activity in the development of improved flexibility and body composition ratios.
Express the emotional benefits developed through physical activity such as stress reduction.
Analyze the benefits of physical activity.
Classify the effects of physical activity on personal wellness such as: relaxation, healthy attitude, and self-image.
Compare personal wellness and identify those components that can benefit from physical activity.
Investigate how physical activity improves overall health and wellness.
Justify the benefits of physical activity
Assess the benefits of physical activity as a motivating factor to positively affect exercise adherence.
Evaluate the value of physical activity for lifelong health and wellness.
Nutrition and Physical Activity
Recognize the relationship between nutrition and physical activity.
Describe how food is fuel to the body as gas is fuel to a car.
Identify nutritious foods that fuel the body for activity such as fruits and vegetables.
Identify foods that are the most efficient fuel for the body (nutritious vs. junk food).
State why nutritious food provides a better source of energy for activity than junk food.
Apply the relationship between nutrition and physical activity.
Discuss the relationship between food intake and its effect on physical activity.
Classify various types of physical activity and the effect on caloric expenditure.
Relate why water consumption is important during physical activity.
Interpret the relationship between caloric expenditure and caloric intake in relationship to body composition including maintaining weight and modifying weight.
Classify various forms of hydration such as water, sports drink, juice, soda, milk, tea, coffee and their effects on physical activity.
Evaluate the relationship between nutrition and physical activity.
Investigate nutrition logs for recording personal caloric intake and analyze the logs for balance using the "My Food Pyramid."
Explore the importance of monitoring hydration based on levels of physical activity.
Investigate the impact nutrients such as protein, carbohydrates, and fats have on physical activity performance.
Choose an exercise and nutrition log for recording personal caloric expenditure and caloric intake and analyze the log for caloric balance.
Assess various types of performance-enhancing drinks and energy drinks and their effect on the body.
Assess various types of nutritional supplements and performance enhancing foods such as energy bars and their effect of the body.
Defend a personal nutrition log to determine ways to improve on diet and exercise.
Assess a personal nutrition log to determine appropriateness of using performance enhancing drinks and foods.
Support the relationship between nutrition and physical activity.
Design a personal nutrition log to correlate with current physical activity levels and nutritional needs.
Discuss causes and effects associated with eating disorders such as: anorexia, bulimia, and binge eating.
Compare popular diets in relationship to the "My Food Pyramid."
Compare various nutritional ergogenic aids and discriminate between the real and implied impacts on the body.
Exercise Adherence
Recognize the factors influencing daily physical activity.
Identify and perform physical activities that are fun, enjoyable, and promote fitness.
Identify and perform physical activities that are fun and that can be performed on a regular basis.
Identify and perform physical activities that can be performed with peers on a regular basis.
Explain the factors influencing daily physical activity.

Discuss the factors that promote or limit physical activity for elementary school students such as peers, parents/family, equipment, facilities, motivation, recreational opportunities, and financial limitations.
Classify factors affecting physical activity as either promoting or limiting.
Discuss factors that limit physical activity and describe strategies to address the factors.
Analyze the factors influencing daily physical activity.
Categorize factors affecting daily physical activity as personal, environmental, or social.
Organize strategies to address the environmental factors that limit physical activity.
Organize strategies to address the social factors that limit physical activity.
Compare and choose strategies to address personal, environmental, and/or social factors that effect maintaining or improving personal physical activity.
Evaluate the factors influencing daily physical activity.
Assess the effectiveness of strategies for overcoming personal, environmental, and/or social factors affecting physical activity level and revise those strategies that have been ineffective.
Rate and prioritize personal motivating factors for adhering to a physically active lifestyle.
Media and Physical Activity
Analyze how the media impacts attitudes towards physical activity.
Discuss various marketing practices and strategies aimed at people interested in improving their fitness levels.
Compare ads/commercials that focus on physical activity and target specific audiences such as runners, weight lifters, to determine the level of influence the media has on participation.
Investigate various marketing practices and strategies influencing consumer decisions on the selection of exercise equipment and programs.
Evaluate the impact of cultural and media perceptions on physical activity.
Assess various marketing practices and strategies that influence consumer decisions on the selection of exercise equipment, programs, and health clubs.
Justify the benefits of current fitness trends.
Discriminate between fitness products and programs that are based on scientific principles and those that are not scientifically based.
Determine a set of criteria to evaluate the validity of personal fitness products.
Determine a set of criteria to evaluate health club facilities.

Physical Activity - Students will demonstrate the ability to use the principles of exercise physiology, social psychology, and biomechanics to design and adhere to a regular, personalized, purposeful program of physical activity consistent with their health, performance, and fitness goals in order to gain health and cognitive/academic benefits.
Aerobic Fitness
Identify and show individual aerobic capacity/cardio respiratory fitness.
Demonstrate activities that improve aerobic capacity/cardio respiratory fitness.
Recognize and perform various aerobic activities such as: jogging and walking and relate their affect on heart rate.
Relate the importance of aerobic capacity/cardio respiratory fitness for a healthy body.
Analyze individual aerobic capacity/cardio respiratory fitness.
Investigate various methods for measuring heart rate such as using a modified perceived exertion scale from 1-5.
Choose and perform activities using the concept of pacing and its importance for aerobic capacity/cardio respiratory fitness.
Calculate personal level of aerobic capacity/ cardiorespiratory fitness through a systematic approach using a standardized fitness test.
Compare and perform various aerobic and anaerobic activities and the effect on heart rate.
Compare various methods for measuring heart rate such as: an instapulse or a stethoscope.
Categorize and demonstrate the three parts of an aerobic workout including warm-up, aerobic phase, and cool down.
Calculate personal aerobic capacity/cardiorespiratory fitness through standardized fitness tests.
Categorize activities to compare the difference between aerobic and anaerobic activity and the effect on heart rate.
Use various methods for measuring individual heart rate.
Distinguish between the three parts of an aerobic workout while performing an aerobic activity.
Evaluate individual aerobic capacity/cardiorespiratory fitness.
Assess and predict aerobic capacity/cardiorespiratory fitness through standardized fitness tests.
Choose and use aerobic activities to improve personal goals related to aerobic capacity/cardio respiratory fitness.
Choose technology to assess individual heart rate during the three phases of an aerobic workout.
Compare and use principles of overload, progression, specificity, regularity, and individuality to enhance aerobic capacity/cardiorespiratory fitness.
Investigate resting heart rate, target heart rate, and maximum heart rate.
Assess and use aerobic activities to improve personal goals related to aerobic capacity/cardio respiratory fitness.
Choose technology to assess individual heart rates for various activities using heart rate monitors or instapulses.
Choose and use principles of overload, progression, specificity, regularity, and individuality to enhance aerobic capacity/cardiorespiratory fitness.
Justify target heart rate to evaluate improvement in aerobic capacity and fitness.
Investigate recovery time in relationship to target heart rate and resting heart rate.
Justify and use aerobic activities to improve personal goals related to aerobic capacity/cardio respiratory fitness.
Choose technology to defend the value of various activities for aerobic capacity/cardio respiratory fitness using heart rate monitors or instapulses.
Assess and use principles of overload, progression, specificity, regularity, and individuality to enhance aerobic capacity/cardiorespiratory fitness.
Defend the use of a target heart rate for improvement of aerobic capacity and fitness.
Assess recovery time and its relationship to improved fitness and increased physical activity.
Analyze and evaluate individual aerobic capacity/cardiorespiratory fitness.
Perform a variety of activities designed to enhance aerobic capacity/cardiorespiratory fitness.
Assess personal levels of aerobic capacity/cardiorespiratory fitness using a standardized test.

Design, execute and revise a personal plan for aerobic capacity/cardiorespiratory fitness based on a fitness assessment and incorporating the principles of overload, progression, specificity, regularity, and individuality.
Use technology to monitor and assess individual heart rate.
Calculate target heart rate to reflect personal activity goals.
Investigate and assess sport/activity specific aerobic capacity/cardiorespiratory fitness programs.
Justify the importance of maintaining a healthy level of cardiorespiratory fitness.
Muscular Strength and Endurance
Identify and show activities for muscular strength and muscular endurance.
Demonstrate activities that improve muscular strength through play.
Recognize and perform appropriate activities that will be used to improve muscular strength.

Categorize muscular strength and muscular endurance activities.

Compare developmentally appropriate muscular strength and muscular endurance activities.
Organize and use muscular strength and muscular endurance task for specific muscle groups of the lower body.
Evaluate individual muscular strength and muscular endurance.
Assess and predict muscular strength and muscular endurance fitness through standardized fitness tests.
Choose and use developmentally appropriate activities to improve personal goals related to muscular strength and endurance fitness.
Compare and use the principles of overload, progression, specificity, regularity, and individuality and how they enhance muscular strength and muscular endurance.
Assess and use developmentally appropriate activities to improve personal goals related to muscular strength and endurance fitness.
Choose and use the principles of overload, progression, specificity, regularity, and individuality to enhance muscular strength and muscular endurance.
Justify and use developmentally appropriate activities to improve personal goals related to muscular strength and endurance fitness
